▋ Tools
───────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────

  This archive can be accessed using valt (the tool that created it) or manually using the
  individual tools listed below. All are free, open-source, and available for macOS and Linux.

  valt       Created this archive. Handles everything automatically if you have it installed.
             https://phoggy.github.io/valt

  age        Encryption tool used to protect the archive contents.
             https://github.com/FiloSottile/age/releases

  minisign   Signing tool used to verify the archive has not been tampered with.
             https://jedisct1.github.io/minisign/

  tar        Standard archive utility, included with macOS and Linux.


▋ Extract with valt
───────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────

  valt extract ${ARCHIVE_NAME} -i <valt.key>


▋ Extract Manually
───────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────

  Open a terminal and change to the directory containing these files, then:

  1. Verify the archive has not been tampered with:

       minisign -V -p minisign.pub -m ${ENCRYPTED_NAME}

     You should see: Signature and comment signature verified

  2. Decrypt the archive:

       age -d -i <key> -o decrypted.tar.xz ${ENCRYPTED_NAME}

     Replace <key> with the path to the private key file. You may be prompted for a passphrase.

  3. Expand the decrypted archive:

       tar xJf decrypted.tar.xz

  4. Verify the payload has not been tampered with:

       minisign -V -p minisign.pub -m ${PAYLOAD_NAME}

     You should see: Signature and comment signature verified

  5. Extract the contents:

       tar xJf ${PAYLOAD_NAME}

  The files are now in your current directory.


